    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a very prudent concern, and I'm glad you're thinking about the safety of your funds. Escrow agents are bound by law and professional ethics to handle the funds with the utmost care. They are typically licensed and insured companies, which means they have to follow strict regulations and can be held accountable if they mishandle funds.\n\nTo minimize the risk of mishandling, escrow agents use secure, often bank-level, systems to manage the funds. They also provide regular statements to both the buyer and the seller, detailing the status of the escrow account and any transactions made. If you have any concerns, you can always ask the escrow agent for more information or even switch to a different agent if necessary.\n\nAdditionally, most real estate contracts include clauses that protect the buyer and seller in the event of a dispute or if the escrow agent fails to fulfill their duties. It's always a good idea to consult with your real estate attorney to understand the specific protections in place for your transaction.",
